<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-859-034  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 859 034.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  Nov 1989 v12 n11 p83(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Busting a bottleneck: high-speed networks tackle growing graphicstraffic problems. (includes related article on protocols andstandards.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Davis, Dwight B.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>High-performance networks are becoming expedient to users ofdata-intensive applications such as scientific visualization andanimation.andP;  A new fiber-optic networking standard, the FiberDistributed Data Interface (FDDI), is gaining popularity due toits more extensive performance capabilities.andP;  Each FDDI networkcan support several attached Ethernets or other LANs; the downfallis that each connection costs more than $10,000.andP;  Companiesconcerned about higher productivity or those who have 50 to 100users accessing a central graphics database may find a high-endnetwork absolutely necessary and well-worth the considerable cost.andO;One problem with FDDI is the inability of its 100Mbps bandwidth toreach its peak rate.andP;  This deficiency is a reflection of networktraffic's throughput which can be improved by refining networkingprotocols.andP;  Even so, FDDI will not meet all graphics transmissionrequirements.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsStandardsNetworksThroughputConnectivityComputer GraphicsPerformance.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>